          "body": "The massacre of Jabesh-gilead (vv. 10-12) is one of the Old Testament's most disturbing passages — and its horror is heightened by the vocabulary the narrator chooses. The command of verse 11 uses charam, the 'sacred ban' or herem — the term reserved in the Torah for the destruction of Canaan's pagan inhabitants (Deuteronomy 7:2; 20:17). The herem was God's instrument for clearing the land of those whose iniquity was full (Genesis 15:16); its application to a fellow Israelite city is the clearest sign that the covenant order has collapsed. Jabesh-gilead's only stated offense is absence from the Mizpah assembly — it did not swear the oath, and cannot therefore be bound by it. The logic that executes Jabesh-gilead is the logic of a community that has made its own oaths the supreme moral category, higher than the lives of those who never consented to them. That 400 virgin women are spared and brought to Shiloh is presented as pragmatic provision; it is never presented as mercy. The text does not record a word from God authorizing any of this."
